Explanations on global competitiveness
In November, the World Economic Forum and the Center for International Development at Harvard University published the Global Competitiveness Report for the year 2001.
In the study covering 75 countries, Finland, the United States, and Canada take the top three positions, while Nicaragua, Nigeria, and Zimbabwe are at the bottom.
(All rankings can be read at www.weforum.com.)
As a co-responsible leader of this annual study, I am often asked what competitiveness actually means.
Besides military competition, is there also an economic competition among the countries?
Is there even any point in saying that Finland is more competitive than, for example, Germany or Italy?
In our report, competitiveness is precisely defined as a country's ability to achieve sustainable economic growth in the medium term—i.e., within a period of five years.
However, this definition does not mean that the competitiveness of one country simultaneously says anything about the lack of competitiveness of another country.
With better political strategies, all countries on Earth could achieve higher growth simultaneously.
Nevertheless, it makes sense to create a ranking of countries based on their growth potential.
Every country is interested in finding out whether its political strategies and public institutions can keep pace with those of other countries in terms of their ability to achieve sustainable economic growth.
In many ways, economic growth is comparable to a sporting competition, in which the gains of one country or region come at the expense of another country or region.
For example, countries compete for internationally mobile capital.
The more foreign direct investment a country can attract, the less another country receives.
This becomes completely clear when countries bid for a specific investment project.
When Intel plans a new semiconductor plant, several countries are invited to submit bids.
The competition for the contract is fierce, and often tax incentives, infrastructure improvements, and even adjustments to the study programs at the local technical university are used to attract the bid.
This year, we determined the competitiveness (growth potential) of a country based on three broad criteria: (1) Technology, (2) Public Institutions, and (3) Macroeconomic Stability.
For each of these categories, we determined key figures whose average values were calculated using a special method in order to create a general growth and competitiveness index.
The Technology criterion refers to a country's ability to drive new developments and to utilize technologies developed elsewhere for its own purposes.
Some countries, such as the USA, Japan, Korea, Israel, and Sweden, strongly invest in research and development and thus achieve high values in the area of innovation.
Other countries, such as Argentina and Brazil, invest less in research and development and therefore achieve little in terms of new products and processes.
Innovation-friendly countries enjoy a high level of prosperity due to these innovations.
In this area, the USA, Canada, and Finland occupy the top three positions on the ranking list.
The criterion "public institutions" refers to the quality of administration.
Is corruption a widespread problem?
Are the courts incorruptible and impartial?
Can one rely on the government to fulfill its obligations properly?
Countries with well-functioning public institutions achieve higher growth rates than countries with corrupt officials and corrupt judges.
High ethical standards promote economic performance.
In this regard, the Nordic countries are leading worldwide, and Finland, Iceland, and Denmark are also the top performers in the ranking.
Corruption is almost unknown in these countries.
Macroeconomic stability is defined by the absence of inflation, a balanced government budget, a realistic exchange rate for the national currency, the ability of businesses and the government to obtain loans in the capital market, and high confidence that the government will meet its financial obligations.
Taking the example of Asia in the late 1990s, we have learned that a macroeconomic crisis can undermine economic growth, even if companies are internationally competitive.
The three leading countries in terms of macroeconomic stability are Singapore, Ireland, and Switzerland.
In our studies on competitiveness, we have noticed that the world economy can be divided into two categories of countries: those that are innovation-friendly and those that are not.
Only about 20 countries are actively involved in the development of new technologies.
In these countries, which are among the richest in the world, a superior system of technological innovations is considered a prerequisite for continuous competitiveness.
Universities must be excellent, state laboratories should reach world-class standards, and government and industry should strongly invest in research and development.
A key factor for future growth in these economies is the proportion of students who attend higher schools and universities after completing compulsory education.
In the USA and Canada, this share is 80%.
For the "non-innovation-friendly" countries, technology is just as important, but most new technologies are imported from abroad and not developed domestically.
Some countries are good at importing new technologies, others are not.
In the past ten or fifteen years, the majority of technology imports occurred within the framework of foreign direct investments.
American companies that heavily invested in Mexico or Taiwanese companies that invested in mainland China also brought new technologies that increased production efficiency in the respective economies of the host countries.
Therefore, it was certainly sensible for the concerned countries to vigorously strive for these foreign investments: they bring not only capital, but also new technologies.
A strength and at the same time a weakness of our analysis of competitiveness is that it is medium-term oriented and does not focus on the next one or two years.
Our rankings are not suitable for assessing short-term cyclical changes in an economy, but they certainly provide insight into the long-term prospects of major economies.
It is therefore ironic that many of the countries taking the top positions this year, such as the USA or Singapore, are actually in a recession, while other countries ranked further down, such as China (rank 39), are not affected by the global recession.
Partly, the slowdown of the economy is linked to the terrorist attacks of September 11, but it is also increasingly becoming clear that the American economy and other economies connected to it through trade and production networks were already sliding into recession before September.
Nevertheless, we believe this to be a temporary cyclical downturn, and that the USA will regain their ability to achieve strong economic growth within the next five years.
